1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:03,320
By now you should be familiar with variables and basic operators,

2

00:00:03,320  -->  00:00:05,280
such as addition and subtraction.

3

00:00:05,280  -->  00:00:09,760
Now we're going to get a little more advanced and talk about shortcut operators.

4

00:00:09,760  -->  00:00:13,680
Shortcut operators, also known as compound assignment operators,

5

00:00:13,680  -->  00:00:17,060
combine an arithmetic operation with an assignment.

6

00:00:17,060  -->  00:00:21,320
These operators make the code more concise and readable.

7

00:00:21,320  -->  00:00:25,860
For basic assignment, let's start off with the simplest implementation.

8

00:00:25,860  -->  00:00:29,100
This operator assigns a value to a variable,

9

00:00:29,100  -->  00:00:31,450
for example, x = 10.

10

00:00:31,450  -->  00:00:34,820
This assigns the value 10 to x.

11

00:00:34,820  -->  00:00:36,660
In the addition assignment,

12

00:00:36,660  -->  00:00:39,620
this operator adds the right operand to

13

00:00:39,620  -->  00:00:43,500
the left operand and assigns the result to the left operand.

14

00:00:43,500  -->  00:00:47,255
Is the equivalent of x = x + 5,

15

00:00:47,255  -->  00:00:52,455
x = 10, x += 5.

16

00:00:52,455  -->  00:00:56,010
This is equivalent to x + x + 5.

17

00:00:56,010  -->  00:00:57,980
X now becomes 15.

18

00:00:57,980  -->  00:01:00,020
In the subtraction assignment,

19

00:01:00,020  -->  00:01:02,980
this operator subtracts the right operand from

20

00:01:02,980  -->  00:01:06,840
the left operand and assigns the result to the left operand.

21

00:01:06,840  -->  00:01:11,050
This is the equivalent of x = x - 3.

22

00:01:11,050  -->  00:01:13,555
You have x = 15,

23

00:01:13,555  -->  00:01:16,450
x -= 3,

24

00:01:16,450  -->  00:01:20,725
and this is the equivalent of x = x - 3.

25

00:01:20,725  -->  00:01:22,560
X now becomes 12.

26

00:01:22,560  -->  00:01:25,160
Now, let's look at how to combine numbers together,

27

00:01:25,160  -->  00:01:28,135
either individually or by each other.

28

00:01:28,135  -->  00:01:30,310
In the multiplication assignment,

29

00:01:30,310  -->  00:01:33,010
this operator multiplies the left operand by

30

00:01:33,010  -->  00:01:36,750
the right operand and assigns the result to the left operand.

31

00:01:36,750  -->  00:01:40,950
This is the equivalent of x = x *2.

32

00:01:40,950  -->  00:01:43,170
We have x = 12,

33

00:01:43,170  -->  00:01:46,110
x * = 2,

34

00:01:46,110  -->  00:01:50,885
and this is the equivalent to x = x * 2.

35

00:01:50,885  -->  00:01:53,230
X now becomes 24.

36

00:01:53,230  -->  00:01:55,690
In the exponentiation assignment,

37

00:01:55,690  -->  00:01:59,250
this operator raises the left operand to the power of

38

00:01:59,250  -->  00:02:03,290
the right operand and assigns the result to the left operand.

39

00:02:03,290  -->  00:02:07,630
Take note that an exponent is asters asterisk,

40

00:02:07,630  -->  00:02:11,050
whereas multiplication is just one asterisk.

41

00:02:11,050  -->  00:02:14,275
An example of exponentiation would be here.

42

00:02:14,275  -->  00:02:19,665
This is the equivalent of x = x asters asterisk 2.

43

00:02:19,665  -->  00:02:26,535
X =3, x asters asters equals 2,

44

00:02:26,535  -->  00:02:35,040
and this is the equivalent of x = x asters asters 2 as x now becomes 9.

45

00:02:35,040  -->  00:02:38,930
Now, let's look at ways to divide numbers into each other.

46

00:02:38,930  -->  00:02:40,790
In the division assignment,

47

00:02:40,790  -->  00:02:43,990
this operator divides the left operand by

48

00:02:43,990  -->  00:02:47,370
the right operand and assigns the result to the left operand.

49

00:02:47,370  -->  00:02:54,995
It is the equivalent of x = x / 4 x = 24.

50

00:02:54,995  -->  00:02:58,470
X / = 4.

51

00:02:58,470  -->  00:03:06,510
This is equivalent to x = x /4 as x now becomes 6.0.

52

00:03:06,510  -->  00:03:08,580
In the floor division assignment,

53

00:03:08,580  -->  00:03:11,440
this operator performs floor division using

54

00:03:11,440  -->  00:03:16,320
the left and right operands and assigns the result to the left operand.

55

00:03:16,320  -->  00:03:22,745
It is the equivalent of x = // 3.

56

00:03:22,745  -->  00:03:28,735
We'll have x = 10, x // =3.

57

00:03:28,735  -->  00:03:36,655
This is the equivalent of x = x // 3 as x now becomes 3.

58

00:03:36,655  -->  00:03:38,570
In the modulus assignment,

59

00:03:38,570  -->  00:03:40,890
this operator takes the modulus using

60

00:03:40,890  -->  00:03:46,170
the left and right operands and assigns them to the result in the left operand.

61

00:03:46,170  -->  00:03:53,820
It's the equivalent of x = x % 5, x =6,

62

00:03:53,820  -->  00:03:57,900
x % = 5,

63

00:03:57,900  -->  00:04:06,895
and this is the equivalent of x = x % 5 as x now becomes 1.

64

00:04:06,895  -->  00:04:09,660
That was a lot of new operators to learn.

65

00:04:09,660  -->  00:04:12,260
Great job. And don't worry if this is still fuzzy.

66

00:04:12,260  -->  00:04:15,400
By practicing your use of these shortcut operators,

67

00:04:15,400  -->  00:04:18,260
you will get much more comfortable with them so you can write

68

00:04:18,260  -->  00:04:21,280
more concise and readable code when you need to

69

00:04:21,280  -->  00:04:25,820
perform these common arithmetic operations and patterns.
